{"type":"message","id":"01172007","parentId":"9c6e6b1f","timestamp":"2026-06-10T07:19:49.670Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the full details for the SÂU HOUSE claw clip:- Product: [MUA 1 TẶNG 1] Kẹp tắc càng cua 6 Răng SÂUHOUSE - Price: 49,000 VND (~$1.96)\n- Weekly sales: 1,140- Monthly sales: 4,375\n- Cumulative sales: 38,367\n- Rating: 4.80- Reviews: 2,468- Category: Hair Clips & Hair Pins: 908552- Sales trend: Stable around 1,000-1,700 per week (has been stable for months, not a flash in the pan)\n\n\n- Price trend: Stable at 49,000 VND (no price wars)\n\nThe sales trajectory shows real staying power—this isn't some viral spike that fades in weeks, it's maintained consistent demand for months. The product ID translates to 1732311961339659361 on TikTok VN, giving me the direct link: https://shop.tiktok.com/en/product/1732311961339659361.\n\nNow I need to dig into the margin picture. The retail price is 49,000 VND (about $1.96 USD), which is solid for Vietnam, but I still need to pin down what 1688 is charging for this item to calculate actual profitability.\n\nThe 1688 search came up empty, which is making me reconsider the opportunity. Let me shift focus and look for a higher-priced product with better margins instead—something in the 35,000+ VND range that would give me more breathing room on the economics. I'm looking at the TikTok Vietnam data for hair accessories and seeing several candidates at better price points: the simple hair stick at 37,536 VND with 2,828 weekly sales, a claw clip at 44,249 VND with 449 weekly sales, and a French-style clip at 45,000 VND. Let me verify which of these actually has the strongest margin potential.\n\nThe simple hair stick is interesting because it has solid volume and a higher price point, but the product link appears to be cut off. I need to figure out which product I was actually analyzing when I mentioned the sales trend.\n\nLooking at the data more carefully, the wood hair stick on Shopee shows 31.65% monthly growth with 273 units in the last 7 days, which is a strong signal. But when I calculate the actual margins at that price point, it falls short of the 70% threshold we're targeting. Let me verify the math on the gross margin calculation to see if this product is actually viable or if I should be looking at something else. I'm realizing the pricing math is quite tight—at ¥5 purchase cost, even a $2.50 selling price only yields about 56% margin after the 45% fixed costs, which falls short of the 70% target. The fundamental issue is that Vietnamese consumers expect lower price points than what the current cost structure allows, so I need to either find cheaper suppliers or reconsider the product category entirely. Looking at the numbers, the VND 49,000 price point gives me enough margin cushion—costing around ¥2.5-3.5 from 1688 yields roughly 166-216% margin even after the 45% operating costs, which comfortably clears the 70% threshold. Let me try searching 1688 with different keywords to find the actual sourcing cost for this product.\n","thinkingSignature":"3831296f5fcf5261dd0ba7f567557363c35a3740aea80c504e2ea1885fafce41"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_6540db9ef18c483ca65e34f1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s -X POST 'https://mcp.sorftime.com/' \\\n  -H \"Authorization: Bearer $(cat /tmp/sorftime_key.txt)\" \\\n  -H 'accept: application/json, text/event-stream' \\\n  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \\\n  -d '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"method\":\"tools/call\",\"params\":{\"name\":\"ali1688_similar_product\",\"arguments\":{\"searchName\":\"hair clip claw clip set 6 teeth\"},\"id\":14}'"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_f21be3c2726e4ee99f84ed5e","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"curl -s -X POST 'https://mcp.sorftime.com/' \\\n  -H \"Authorization: Bearer $(cat /tmp/sorftime_key.txt)\" \\\n  -H 'accept: application/json, text/event-stream' \\\n  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \\\n  -d '{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.