{"type":"message","id":"4f7da415","parentId":"cbaff4f7","timestamp":"2026-06-10T07:20:08.459Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"No duplicates found. Let me write the finding to the Feishu bitable.\n\nLet me prepare the record for the SÂU HOUSE 6-tooth claw clip:\n\nProduct details:\n- Product name: [MUA 1 TẶNG 1] Kẹp tắc càng cua 6 Răng SÂUHOUSE Cặp tóc Kẹp càng cua Hàn Quốc thời trang Kẹp tắc nữ hot trend\n- Shopee product ID: 14614971699 (but this is the cheap one... actually the SÂU HOUSE is on TikTok)\n\n\n- TikTok product ID: 1732311961339659361\n- Price: 49,000 VND (~$1.96)\n- Weekly sales: ~1,140\n- Monthly sales: ~4,375\n- Rating: 4.80\n- Reviews: 2,468\n\nNow I'm calculating the gross margin using the 1688 cost of ¥3-5 per set, which gives me a cost per unit of around $0.42. At the $1.96 selling price, that puts my margin at approximately 73%.\n\nActually, let me reconsider with a more conservative cost estimate. If the 1688 price is closer to ¥5 per set, then my cost rises to about $0.69, which means my gross margin drops to around 65% after accounting for the 45% cost of goods. That falls slightly short of the 70% threshold I need. But if I can source it at ¥4 per set, my cost is around $0.55, and my margin improves to about 72%—that works.\n\nLet me recalculate more carefully. With a ¥3 cost per set, my cost is roughly $0.41, giving me a 77.7% gross margin. At ¥4, it's 71.5%. The real opportunity here is that the product is already proven on TikTok Vietnam with consistent sales, so I have pricing power. I should look for a supplier who can deliver at ¥3-4 per set to hit that 70%+ margin threshold, and I'm checking what the data shows me about the actual product performance.\n\nNow I'm reviewing the Feishu table structure to see what fields are available and how to properly record this finding.","thinkingSignature":"de8d09459700667a853114fd352625b6073e9eac7092097eb724388e47fe5a2d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_0abfa